commit_message:
Remove cells v2 transition code from update_instance

Per the TODO in this code, we can remove this transition
code for cells v2 which was added before the instance was
created in conductor. When updating an instance, if the
instance isn't in a cell yet (no id) and the build request was
not found, then either it was already deleted or there is an
instance mapping, because we create the instance mapping before
deleting the build request in conductor. So if the instance
mapping is also not found, then the instance is gone and we can
raise a 404 error.

Change-Id: I6d231320e0825d5c89adfa9caf8b72c59d2a1502

commit_message:
Move the request-helpers spec for keystonemiddleware to attic

Move the request-helpers backlog spec for keystonemiddleware to the
attic. At the Denver PTG (2019) we discussed this spec. We are in a
very different space from where we were at the time of proposal, and
if there is a desire to revisit this specific specification it can
be brought back from the attic.

Change-Id: I3e1ab025bb998b14c0a71854b9109d9f29b25ee9

commit_message:
Move endpoint-enforcement-middleware spec to attic

At the Denver PTG, it was agreed that the endpoint-enforcement spec for
the endforcement of endpoint filtering in middleware is not something
we are looking to implement. The spec can be recovered from the attic
if there is interest in the work.

Change-Id: I9e13969714f56a166c6394934514d7b95b849e05

commit_message:
Cleanup update_instance cell mapping handling

Targeting the instance mapping cell context is redundant now
that _get_instance stores the targeted context on the
instance._context object when it's retrieved. This happens when
the REST API controller code gets the instance from the compute
API before we ever get to the update_instance method, and
PUT /servers/{server_id} is the only way to get here anyway.

So we can remove all of this older code which was doing an explicit
cell target operation which came before the instance._context
was targeted in _get_instance.

Change-Id: I30b5d4378724b718c6aa8e52ce2f4412d968fc7d

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-11 05:01:27.000000000', 'message': 'Allow skipping bootstrap steps in gate check

Add 3 new environment variables during gate-check-commit and
bootstrap-ansible which allow for skipping the ansible-runtime venv
build, the bootstrap-aio role execution, and the OSA role clone.

Any value set to the skip variables will cause the execution of
that item to skip.

The environment variables added are:
SKIP_OSA_RUNTIME_VENV_BUILD
SKIP_OSA_BOOTSTRAP_AIO
SKIP_OSA_ROLE_CLONE

These will be used to skip the steps in the gate as we will shift
to running these in the Zuul pre-run phase. They can be run multiple
times, but skipping them will decrease execution time.

Change-Id: I96d73cf196fb4ede8ec163cac2971a45c757106f

commit_message:
Allow skipping bootstrap steps in gate check

Add 3 new environment variables during gate-check-commit and
bootstrap-ansible which allow for skipping the ansible-runtime venv
build, the bootstrap-aio role execution, and the OSA role clone.

Any value set to the skip variables will cause the execution of
that item to skip.

The environment variables added are:
SKIP_OSA_RUNTIME_VENV_BUILD
SKIP_OSA_BOOTSTRAP_AIO
SKIP_OSA_ROLE_CLONE

These will be used to skip the steps in the gate as we will shift
to running these in the Zuul pre-run phase. They can be run multiple
times, but skipping them will decrease execution time.

Change-Id: I96d73cf196fb4ede8ec163cac2971a45c757106f

subject: Retiring neutron-lbaas and neutron-lbaas-dashboard
messages:
[{'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2019-05-10 22:01:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2019-05-10 22:02:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There are a couple more mentions of neutron-lbaas as requirements for third-party projects in zuul.d/projects.yaml and I'm not sure what to do with them. Should I remove them here, or leave it up to those projects to rework their own stuff?"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-11 04:41:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

There's a process for retiring, follow it completely:
https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/drivers.html#retiring-a-project

Especially: I miss in the commit message a link to an announcement - and like to see *all* relevant patches up and linked via Needed-by/depends-on.

also, you need two patches for project-config."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-11 04:43:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> There are a couple more mentions of neutron-lbaas as requirements
 > for third-party projects in zuul.d/projects.yaml and I'm not sure
 > what to do with them. Should I remove them here, or leave it up to
 > those projects to rework their own stuff?

You need to remove all mention of these projects from zuul.d/projects.yaml and also from zuul files in other repos. We cannot retire a repo that is still in use. Especially update openstack-zuul-jobs - and make the final change dependend on all these removals."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2019-05-11 09:41:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2019-05-11 09:59:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Wait, so what has to depend-on what? There's like 5 different patches for this and I'm not actually sure which is the higher level change."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-11 09:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

you need two project-config changes and a couple of others changes, please read the link I gave you...'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-11 10:02:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Read the document, it explains it nicely.

Check also https://review.opendev.org/#/c/656855/ - that one is easier since it has no governance change and does not need updating in other changes. But the final project-config change can only merge once no project has "required-projects:" lines for the retired repos on any branches.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2019-05-11 10:17:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-11 10:24:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

gerritbot/channels.yaml could be part of patch 4 as well..

commit_message:
Add ability to specify multiple search domains

Especially when deploying in an environment where we are deploying
into a subdomain, we need the ability to specify multiple search
domains to be added to /etc/resolv.conf.

Change-Id: I45231fc53c24e1aad3f4a0026696954096430586

This might require some more discussion.  At one point we were trying to remove the custom log stuff in oslo.log and make it more of a configuration tool for the built-in python logging.  I think Doug was leading that work so it would be good to hear his input on what direction we should go here.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2018-08-15 13:18:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> This might require some more discussion.  At one point we were
 > trying to remove the custom log stuff in oslo.log and make it more
 > of a configuration tool for the built-in python logging.  I think
 > Doug was leading that work so it would be good to hear his input on
 > what direction we should go here.

We've talked about adding some options to make common configurations easier, so that deployers don't have to use the external logging configuration files to do things like set up JSON logging. With that in mind, adding an option to turn on trace logging makes sense.

On the other hand, I thought we were trying to do away with trace level logging entirely, so I'm not sure we want to expose it this way.

How do the other log handlers deal with that level? Does the syslog handler work properly, for example? And the systemd handler?"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-08-16 05:36:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> On the other hand, I thought we were trying to do away with trace level logging entirely, so I'm not sure we want to expose it this way.

The need in nova for this is pretty specific to some debug logging in a critical section of the nova-scheduler which will noticeably slow down processing of a scheduling request and because people run the scheduler with debug logging since that's the only way currently to get enough details about why scheduling requests fail (the scheduler filters log at debug). The scheduler filter debug logging is the key, but this other piece that's also at debug is less relevant and definitely more of a TRACE level, i.e. we'd have an option to log it if you really wanted, but it's definitely low-level. Alternatively, we do something about the scheduler filter logging to make that more consumable outside of debug logs (ideally we'd have this long-term, but it's much more complicated), or we add a nova-specific [scheduler]/trace_logging option to nova (easy, but then you could have one-offs of this kind of thing rather than a single universal trace option in all configs).

> How do the other log handlers deal with that level? Does the syslog handler work properly, for example? And the systemd handler?

I have no idea."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2018-08-16 14:51:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> > On the other hand, I thought we were trying to do away with trace
 > level logging entirely, so I'm not sure we want to expose it this
 > way.
 > 
 > The need in nova for this is pretty specific to some debug logging
 > in a critical section of the nova-scheduler which will noticeably
 > slow down processing of a scheduling request and because people run
 > the scheduler with debug logging since that's the only way
 > currently to get enough details about why scheduling requests fail
 > (the scheduler filters log at debug). The scheduler filter debug
 > logging is the key, but this other piece that's also at debug is
 > less relevant and definitely more of a TRACE level, i.e. we'd have
 > an option to log it if you really wanted, but it's definitely
 > low-level. Alternatively, we do something about the scheduler
 > filter logging to make that more consumable outside of debug logs
 > (ideally we'd have this long-term, but it's much more complicated),
 > or we add a nova-specific [scheduler]/trace_logging option to nova
 > (easy, but then you could have one-offs of this kind of thing
 > rather than a single universal trace option in all configs).

OK, I would definitely prefer to have 1 option for this instead of a bunch of application-specific options.

 > > How do the other log handlers deal with that level? Does the
 > syslog handler work properly, for example? And the systemd handler?
 > 
 > I have no idea.

In what sort of environments have you seen the trace logging enabled? I would hate to have --trace turn into a kill switch because logging falls over on application startup.

For regular file logging it should just work, but some of those other loggers translate levels between our numbers and well-defined settings."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2018-08-16 16:18:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

 > >

 > 
 > For regular file logging it should just work, but some of those

Maybe we just document that this is a custom logging level that may not work with other handlers?  Even if we verified that every handler in oslo.log works, I believe it would be possible for someone to configure an external handler and we have no way of knowing whether it would work.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2018-08-16 16:20:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-09-07 00:17:47.000000000', 'message': "WIP: RFE: Add CONF.trace option

LOG.trace() has been around for awhile but there isn't a way
to configure it's usage in services like nova-scheduler. You can
enable it via CONF.default_log_levels, but that's used in services
like nova-scheduler to configure default log levels for dependent
libraries, not for the service itself.

This adds a 'trace' config option that is similar to the CONF.debug
option except for it sets the root log level to TRACE if enabled.

Change-Id: Ib083f86cc43ddd7ec98e0d45a115ac295d6c6fb4
Closes-Bug: #1620789
"}, {'created': '2016-09-07 00:22:27.000000000', 'message': "WIP: RFE: Add CONF.trace option

to configure it's usage in services like nova-scheduler. You can
enable it via CONF.default_log_levels, but that's used in services
like nova-scheduler to configure default log levels for dependent
libraries, not for the service itself.

This adds a 'trace' config option that is similar to the CONF.debug
option except for it sets the root log level to TRACE if enabled.

Change-Id: Ib083f86cc43ddd7ec98e0d45a115ac295d6c6fb4

commit_message:
RFE: Add CONF.trace option

LOG.trace() has been around for awhile but there isn't a way
to configure it's usage in services like nova-scheduler. You can
enable it via CONF.default_log_levels, but that's used in services
like nova-scheduler to configure default log levels for dependent
libraries, not for the service itself.

This adds a 'trace' config option that is similar to the CONF.debug
option except for it sets the root log level to TRACE if enabled.

Change-Id: Ib083f86cc43ddd7ec98e0d45a115ac295d6c6fb4
Closes-Bug: #1620789

commit_message:
Update Python 3 test runtimes for Train

This goal is to implement the process set out in the 2018-10-24 Python
Update Process TC resolution[1], for the Train cycle to ensure unit
testing is in place for all of the Tested Runtimes for Train[2].
In practice, this generally means adding unit tests for Python 3.7 and dropping
unit tests for Python 3.5. Using the Zuul template for Train will ensure that
all projects that support Python3 will be tested against the agreed runtime
versions, and make it easier to update them in future.

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20181024-python-update-process.html
[2]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/train.html

Change-Id: Ifb40dd40e716c0f07cafce4425e4ac13619d2085
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/641878/

commit_message:
Add upper-constraints enforcement for local reqs

This adds the use of upper constraints in our tox environments. Jobs
like openstack-tox-py27 have started failing due to trying to install
lib versions that only support Python 3.

The 'generate' target keeps the unconstrained deps since we actually do
need the latest installed for that.

Updates the requirements-integration job to run using py36 since that
now fails with running under py27. This should get the job to pass until
we are able to rewrite it to not be a legacy job.

NOTE(dmllr): updated install_command to include local constraints file

Change-Id: I2598503c2d4397d7efbb03a76df9a4e91dd0c1cf
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8bad9fe19d09eb2e49fd44b92c57ee5acf85b558)

commit_message:
Cap keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

NOTE(tonyb): The more modern branches allow networkx >= 2.0.  These
version are explictly blocked on queens so we no longer squash
I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876

NOTE(dmllr): Fix typo.

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

commit_message:
Trivial: Adds comments and tests for scheduler

This patch adds a comment for aggregate operation in scheduler utils
since aggregate requests to placement has a bit complex or/and logic.

This patch also fixes scheduler util tests where there was
inconsistency between the name of mocked compute node objects and
mocked request spec objects.

This is a follow up of https://review.opendev.org/#/c/650878/.

Change-Id: Ic00f8f39200b46908f474c7fc09415063a730ce2

I am really worried that this is an accidental breaking API change.

It is really an API that was bodged in for nova-net and neutron cross compatibility, similar to secuirty_groups stuff.

Normally I would say we need a new micro version for this kind of change, but this API is deprecated, so that doesn't really make sense:
https://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/compute/?expanded=remove-disassociate-fixed-ip-removefixedip-action-deprecated-detail#remove-disassociate-fixed-ip-removefixedip-action-deprecated

As always, I am willing to change my mind if I have this all confused."}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2019-05-13 14:55:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2019-05-13 15:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Been talking about other fixes, such as returning http conflict if there is a floating ip already on a port.

However, normally that would need a microversion change, but it makes the API do less because its really confusing when it does "more". It may break people, but it feels like it does that in quite a safe sort of way. I am on the fence about the best option.

Probably the best change is to make sure no CLI and SDK provides this API.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2019-05-13 15:17:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

given this has been around years, and is dangerous, lets just abandon it. Please restore if you want to restart the discussion.'}]

commit_message:
Disassociate floating ip when fixed ip is removed

When fixed ip is removed from an instance, its associated
floating ip should be disassociated. Otherwise the port_id
and fixed_ip will remain in the floating ip info.

Change-Id: Ia482b76a9fba73a19e19eb323395cc71c7e6116a
Closes-Bug: #1525101
Co-Authored-by: Bo Chi <shcbo@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fix bandit failure B105 in keystone fernet

>> Issue: [B105:hardcoded_password_string] Possible hardcoded password: '/etc/keystone/fernet-keys'
   Severity: Low Confidence: Medium
      Location: docker/keystone/keystone-fernet/fetch_fernet_tokens.py:27
         More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b105_hardcoded_password_string.html

Ignore bandit failures on this line.

Change-Id: I9828c23e4bcec7553a69aa5f20e990e0ef0538ea
Closes-Bug: #1828416

commit_message:
Log trace when updating host states

Because host_state.update() is called for all compute nodes, logging
within update() will cause a performance hit with any reasonable number
of compute nodes. So this drops the logging in update() down to trace,
so even with debug logging on, the performance hit is not seen (as
much).

For reference, here are performance numbers from select_destinations()
with and without debug logging in an environment with 400 compute hosts.
http://paste.openstack.org/show/566153/

Closes-Bug: #1620692
Change-Id: I8bba16c94c2bdd114bc011382747ebca25ea5a50

commit_message:
Add Sonobuoy plugin config from yaml

Adds a yaml path for providing additional yaml that will be stored in a
secret and provided to the plugin. Values can be added to plugin_values
that will result in being needed configuration and expected values
for tests. Utilizes the extra-volumes functionality as described [0]

[0]: https://github.com/heptio/sonobuoy/blob/master/docs/plugins.md#writing-your-own-plugin

commit_message:
Rename parameters in call() of nova/image/glance.py

Snapshot creation of a server using nova API fails if image contains
"version","context" or "method" as metadata properties.
Image metadata is passed as an argument to _create_v2(nova/image/glance.py)
which is then passed to call (nova/image/glance.py) as kwargs.
This function already takes in context, method, and version arguments
so any of these metadata properties would cause the snapshot to fail.

Prefix parameter names with an underscore.

Change-Id: I3839b8258d27c0dcf7780c00ca400696e2be5223
Closes-Bug: #1717547

commit_message:
Temporary fix of failing aria2 on centos

Added get_url as an alternate downloader, when aria2 is failing
due to SSL error. Now it happens for CentOS and is reproducable.
We probably won't need this patch once aria2 package will be fixed.

Change-Id: I7770c5417feacfc43a3ad8801125603a55ba9ea8

commit_message:
Provide environment to enable ml2-ovs

As ovn is the default plugin, provide an environment file to still
keep the ml2-ovs. NFV deployments are not yet ready for the migration,
until all ovn gaps are addressed.

commit_message:
Update the gate hooks to install proper docker package

The way gate_hook.sh tries to find the proper package to install is
sub-optimal, and misses in case there is another package containing the
package name as a substring.
Updating the file to work the same way as in [1].

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-dynamic-routing/commit/c27bb1f190a60d201d616bebd42c60dae6afa545

Change-Id: I726f993ef9d593f13abef55fca6cc2c0a2d353c7

commit_message:
Update the tox.ini with '0' concurrency

There is an issue with the ostestr package that it sends a 'None' value
if it is not explicitly specified.
The stestr package does not accept it well, and an exception is thrown.
There is a fix in the pipe [1], but we need to get DragonFlow working.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/651275/

Change-Id: If9d18965048cc5ac20d351b7172b50d0a1d0f2cc

commit_message:
Cap keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

NOTE(tonyb): The more modern branches allow networkx >= 2.0.  These
version are explictly blocked on queens so we no longer squash
I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876

NOTE(dmllr): Fix typo.

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>
(cherry picked from commit 00b2bcf7d664b1526b4eefe157c33113206d6251)
(cherry picked from commit c59a15adbf9f6c0df161f74f0b38ba0d47fe2185)
(cherry picked from commit e91a7887ba83f0906960188e3c1173f38e5760c8)

commit_message:
fixing timing

The parameter 'timing' got lost in translation in this stack.

python-openstackclient -> osc-lib -> openstacksdk -> keystoneauth

keystoneauth only understand 'collect_timing' while the others only
conveys 'timing'. Therefore, we have to make the proper translation.

Change-Id: I6c1182bb1d8c04791a573fb556197440360a2bb9
Story: #2005315
Task: #30222
(cherry picked from commit 21bb881d03d431995c654313db7ba29035b3bcb1)
(cherry picked from commit 17e079c3088ce5c54d0df726c95bebbb427f4ab2)

why need this change? kubenetes has been retired from kolla'}, {'account_id': 23717, 'date': '2018-08-13 10:59:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Completely understood that KK8s retired but TipleO and Openstack-Helm still support kolla images. And both projects have motive towards Openstack on Kubernetes, so that way keeping this is still reasonable.

commit_message:
Modify udev rule for VF representor rename

It seems that if we have more than one NIC in SR_IOV switchdev mode,
the names of the represntors will overlap for those NICS,
like pf0vf0 for the first port of the first NIC and pf0vf0 for the
first port of the second NIC, so we need to rename the VF
representor as "<sriov_pf_name>_<vf_num>" "enp3s0f0_2" in order to
be unique and consistent

Change-Id: I25263926e736ed0e4fafaa9aa9891e5961226462
Closes-Bug: #1823526
(cherry picked from commit 22aeee1b87731618356f2792d49795a01f40ec19)

commit_message:
Modify udev rule for VF representor rename

It seems that if we have more than one NIC in SR_IOV switchdev mode,
the names of the represntors will overlap for those NICS,
like pf0vf0 for the first port of the first NIC and pf0vf0 for the
first port of the second NIC, so we need to rename the VF
representor as "<sriov_pf_name>_<vf_num>" "enp3s0f0_2" in order to
be unique and consistent

Change-Id: I25263926e736ed0e4fafaa9aa9891e5961226462
Closes-Bug: #1823526
(cherry picked from commit 22aeee1b87731618356f2792d49795a01f40ec19)

[{'created': '2019-05-13 13:03:06.000000000', 'message': "Handle collections.abc deprecations

The use of ABC classes directly from collections has been deprecated in
3.x versions of Python. The direction is to use the classes defined in
collections.abc. Python 2.7 does not have this, but Python 3.8 will be
dropping the backwards compatibility to use the old location.

Six also does not have support for this yet, so in the mean time to make
sure we don't run into issues as folks try to move to 3.8, and to get
rid of deprecation warnings in logs, this handles importing from the
preferred location and falls back if it not available.

Change-Id: Ifd2141ff4d8b5e9ca707860b9e464f8a19fefe74
"}]
commit_message:
Handle collections.abc deprecations

The use of ABC classes directly from collections has been deprecated in
3.x versions of Python. The direction is to use the classes defined in
collections.abc. Python 2.7 does not have this, but Python 3.8 will be
dropping the backwards compatibility to use the old location.

Six also does not have support for this yet, so in the mean time to make
sure we don't run into issues as folks try to move to 3.8, and to get
rid of deprecation warnings in logs, this handles importing from the
preferred location and falls back if it not available.

Change-Id: Ifd2141ff4d8b5e9ca707860b9e464f8a19fefe74

commit_message:
Update Python 3 test runtimes for Train

This goal is to implement the process set out in the 2018-10-24 Python
Update Process TC resolution[1], for the Train cycle to ensure unit
testing is in place for all of the Tested Runtimes for Train[2].
In practice, this generally means adding unit tests for Python 3.7 and dropping
unit tests for Python 3.5. Using the Zuul template for Train will ensure that
all projects that support Python3 will be tested against the agreed runtime
versions, and make it easier to update them in future.

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20181024-python-update-process.html
[2]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/train.html

Change-Id: I095770fabafda1a7735c2711d4df061a6dc2bb78
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/641878/

> Could you please provide a link for the error you saw? I didn't

To be honest, I am not sure whether it is a change we need. Before these change in trove-scenario-mariadb-single tests logs we were getting this messages:
`
2019-04-24 15:15:52.898 | + diskimage_builder/lib/img-functions:trap_cleanup:38                              :   exit 1
/opt/stack/trove/.tox/trovestack/lib/python3.6/site-packages/diskimage_builder/lib/outfilter.py:29: DeprecationWarning: invalid escape sequence \+
  IGNORE_LINES = re.compile('(set \+o|xtrace)')
ERROR: InvocationError for command /opt/stack/trove/integration/scripts/trovestack gate-tests mariadb mariadb-supported-single (exited with code 1)
`
After problem investigation, it occured that image builder always exits with status 1. Trovestack scripts have `set -e` option so thay fail whenever something returns non-zero status. This change allows us ignoring image builder status.

After this change, trove-scenario-mariadb-single goes one step further:
`

  IGNORE_LINES = re.compile('(set \+o|xtrace)')

Image /home/zuul/images/ubuntu_mariadb.qcow2 was built successfully.

Glance upload failed!
ERROR: InvocationError for command /opt/stack/trove/integration/scripts/trovestack gate-tests mariadb mariadb-supported-single (exited with code 1)
`
Unfortunately, there are new problems which are not solved by this patch."}, {'account_id': 6732, 'date': '2019-05-10 22:28:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add upper constraint for diskimage-builder

It seems that starting with version 2.21 of diskimage-builder Trove
scenario tests starts to fail.

As we cannot exclude 2.21 version from requirements due to global
requirements, this patch ignores return value of the builder.

Further investigation should be made to find what exactly caused tests
fail and eventually, integrating new diskimage-builder may be done.

Change-Id: Ie661309bb69bcd2c1d2fbef90e048e65016ab1d4
Signed-off-by: Kasper Hasior <k.hasior@samsung.com>

[{'created': '2019-05-07 14:49:39.000000000', 'message': 'api-ref: fix mention of all_tenants filter for non-admins

The API reference for listing servers says that the all_tenants
filter parameter is available for non-admins which is likely
a mistake because of it being in the _get_server_search_options
method, but all_tenants is admin-only by default policy because
of the os_compute_api:servers:index:get_all_tenants and
os_compute_api:servers:detail:get_all_tenants policy rules.

This change fixes the API reference to remove all_tenants from
the list of non-admin filter parameters and also adds a note to
the _get_server_search_options method to avoid future confusion.

Change-Id: I0e937afbdf8e19d2efd626047913d4c8a9b88b76
Closes-Bug: #1828042
'}]
commit_message:
api-ref: fix mention of all_tenants filter for non-admins

The API reference for listing servers says that the all_tenants
filter parameter is available for non-admins which is likely
a mistake because of it being in the _get_server_search_options
method, but all_tenants is admin-only by default policy because
of the os_compute_api:servers:index:get_all_tenants and
os_compute_api:servers:detail:get_all_tenants policy rules.

This change fixes the API reference to remove all_tenants from
the list of non-admin filter parameters and also adds a note to
the _get_server_search_options method to avoid future confusion.

Change-Id: I0e937afbdf8e19d2efd626047913d4c8a9b88b76
Closes-Bug: #1828042

commit_message:
PowerMax driver - Rapid TDEV Deallocation

Changes made to adding & removing volumes from RDF enabled storage groups
when using new 91 endpoints force flag is needed in established groups.

Volume delete workflow no longer calls deallocation function seperately, this is now
included in volume delete process.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
and resubmit a new change-set.

Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Choose whether to ignore/warn/crit on failed actions

This commit adds a new option to check_crm named --failedactions
Possible options are 'warning', 'critical', or anything else (which is
considered equivalent to 'ignore').
The default is 'critical' to be backward compatible.

Change-Id: I5908f5f4b7d77219280dfe896ea938459c6b23bd
Partial-Bug: #1796400

commit_message:
Add upper constraints to tox

Sphinx has released a version that has dropped python2 support but this
is handled in upper-constraints if we were properly including it in the
tox.ini deps.

NOTE: fixed url for stein

Change-Id: I3d0a91ccef9693fd46e19292f4bb21c1ec9a9a19
(cherry picked from commit a0612328b3fa670801e720fb0668d35b37a13ebc)

are added/removed. However, the number of chassis where a
gateway can be hosted is limited by the constant MAX_GW_CHASSIS.

Trivial Change: Debug logging information is added to
get_candidates_for_scheduling() to provide more information when no
chassis information is available for a physnet.

Disable metadata_csum when creating ext4 filesystems

Cirros can't mount a ephemeral partition if its enabled.

Story: #2004604
Task: #28499
(cherry picked from commit 71f0256b1d951229c22aea2784c0f0711f045e54)

commit_message:
Enable ironic notifications

This patch adds an ironic notifier that sends notifications to
ironic endpoint /v1/events. The events are triggered by port
updates and deletions. Only ports with vnic_type=baremetal are
honored.

commit_message:
Removes insecure parameter from barbican client

This removes the parameter insecure in the client creation as this
no longer exists in the client. It also changes the client class
to be called as other clients in openstack using sessions

Change-Id: I3cb7ed4255f8996b8bfd9a3e1edba6de50f4e492
Closes-Bug: #1800819

commit_message:
Update Python 3 test runtimes for Train

This goal is to implement the process set out in the 2018-10-24 Python
Update Process TC resolution[1], for the Train cycle to ensure unit
testing is in place for all of the Tested Runtimes for Train[2].
In practice, this generally means adding unit tests for Python 3.7 and dropping
unit tests for Python 3.5. Using the Zuul template for Train will ensure that
all projects that support Python3 will be tested against the agreed runtime
versions, and make it easier to update them in future.

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20181024-python-update-process.html
[2]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/train.html

Change-Id: I06e6c071b8bd369c8a66bade2490f65070fd0665
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/641878/

The 'generate' target keeps the unconstrained deps since we actually do
need the latest installed for that.

commit_message:
Add upper-constraints enforcement for local reqs

This adds the use of upper constraints in our tox environments. Jobs
like openstack-tox-py27 have started failing due to trying to install
lib versions that only support Python 3.

The 'generate' target keeps the unconstrained deps since we actually do
need the latest installed for that.

Updates the requirements-integration job to run using py36 since that
now fails with running under py27. This should get the job to pass until
we are able to rewrite it to not be a legacy job.

NOTE(dmllr): updated install_command to include local constraints file

Change-Id: I2598503c2d4397d7efbb03a76df9a4e91dd0c1cf
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
py3: deal with more subordinate dependencies

Ensure subordinate py3 packages are installed if their py2
counter-parts are currently installed for neutron-openvswitch.
In this case we had missed python(3)-neutron-fwaas.

Change-Id: I9d5e7c2ad034cd7bdf9cbf292b9107577860dac1
Closes-Bug: #1828259

commit_message:
Store gate scenario configuration on Zuul executor

Playbooks other than the run playbook will require access to the gate
check scenario vars, which are computed dynamically. Add a pre-playbook
implementing the dynamic behavior and store a vars file in the Zuul
executor workspace that can be used as an ansible "vars_file" in other
Zuul playbooks.

Change-Id: I5723aef8c1123b2ce60140041fee78720f67e0af

Baremetal deployments should follow OVB deployments

undercloud vm.

commit_message:
Change Undercloud log file name for consistency

When the Undercloud is installed we create a
tar file called as undercloud-install-<timestamp>.tar.bzip2

When this file is unzipped the result file is called
install-undercloud.log which is not consistent with the
tar file and with the previous versions log name.

Change-Id: I5be6d8b7c3b4ce76ad90cf2bb466ba19dab44059

commit_message:
Give priority to the custom container images file if used

We need to give higher priority to the env file using
a custom container images.

If we dont do this, when executing the Undercloud install
the default values from undercloud_parameters.yaml will
override the custom and needed values

Closes-Bug: 1790826
Change-Id: I0a7f153139d4e321877955d51f857a96ae5cec5a

commit_message:
Check Apache ssl dir when determining restart map

If the certificates change then services needs to be restarted. This
change adds the SSL directory to the restart map to ensure any
certificate changes trigger a restart.

Also, if the certificates change we need to pass those on to
nova-compute.

Change-Id: I4cb2f760c26f0804d3cb7466c8aa741d5e0ec314
Closes-Bug: 1828530

commit_message:
Check Apache ssl dir when determining restart map

If the certificates that Apache is using change then services needs
to be restarted. This change adds the SSL directory to the restart
map to ensure any certificate changes trigger a restart.

Change-Id: Idbdceb5acd80c06a2bde02f9df88a9d9fd2404fb
Closes-Bug: 1828530

commit_message:
Remove obsolete rally jobs

Remove legacy-rally-dsvm-py35-cinder, cinder has an in-tree job called
cinder-rally-task now. Note that legacy-rally-dsvm-py35-cinder only
run on master.

job called neutron-rally-task now. The legacy job runs only on master.

commit_message:
Resolve instability in json_ingester test_execute_exec_api_rows

Occassionally the unit test congress.tests.datasources.json_ingester.
test_exec_api.TestExecApiManager.test_execute_exec_api_rows
fails inside eventlet code even though the eventlet call is mocked
out.

This patch adds a new mock path because eventlet.spawn_n
somehow redirects there. Hopefully it resolves the occassional
instability gets.

Sample error:
  File "/home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/congress/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/greenpool.py", line 115, in spawn_n
    function, args, kwargs, True)
  File "/home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/congress/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/mock/mock.py", line 1062, in __call__
    return _mock_self._mock_call(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/congress/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/mock/mock.py", line 1128, in _mock_call
    ret_val = effect(*args, **kwargs)
  File "congress/tests/datasources/json_ingester/test_exec_api.py", line 27, in mock_spawn_execute
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/congress/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/greenpool.py", line 99, in _spawn_n_impl
    self._spawn_done(coro)
  File "/home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/congress/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/greenpool.py", line 131, in _spawn_done
    self.coroutines_running.remove(coro)
KeyError: <greenlet.greenlet object at 0x7fd975681cd0>

Change-Id: I72e11a67cf1cd3ff3fbc574f2d6e91df17d63d9c

commit_message:
Fix the import for filter_utils

Changed from importing utils and calling it via utils.filter_utils
to a proper import utils.__init__.py didn't export it so the way it
was called probably worked for python 2 only.

This way is a more ubiquitous way of calling it.

Change-Id: Ie6a073dc286f0d8704c67f8295dfd76bce7897bb

commit_message:
Move entirely to dynamic job execution

If the gate job's scenario, action, or install method are not
directly provided via vars, attempt to identify them from the Zuul
job name.

commit_message:
Add upper-constraints enforcement for local reqs

This adds the use of upper constraints in our tox environments. Jobs
like openstack-tox-py27 have started failing due to trying to install
lib versions that only support Python 3.

The 'generate' target keeps the unconstrained deps since we actually do
need the latest installed for that.

Updates the requirements-integration job to run using py36 since that
now fails with running under py27. This should get the job to pass until
we are able to rewrite it to not be a legacy job.

NOTE(dmllr): updated install_command to include local constraints file

Change-Id: I2598503c2d4397d7efbb03a76df9a4e91dd0c1cf
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Cap networkx, keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

NetworkX released 2.3, dropping support for Python 2.

https://github.com/networkx/networkx/blob/master/doc/news.rst

Includes squash of commit:
Change-Id: I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876
(cherry picked from commit d78bf07af26b6ff485722838b1c11e43796a115b)

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
(cherry picked from commit 00b2bcf7d664b1526b4eefe157c33113206d6251)
(cherry picked from commit c59a15adbf9f6c0df161f74f0b38ba0d47fe2185)
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

Dropping the py35 testing

Train or stable/stein[2].

As per below ML thread, we are good to drop the py35 (and older)
testing now:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2019-April/005097.html

commit_message:
Add retry for backup get_url task

As CentOS aria2 package is still only in epel-testing repo,
get_url tends to fail with timout errors, which forces to do rechecks
and creates extra load on gates.
So we're adding retries for this task and extending timeout.

Change-Id: I26d3c9338247ffc789bf4a5291e65e954151cc51

commit_message:
fixing timing

The parameter 'timing' got lost in translation in this stack.

python-openstackclient -> osc-lib -> openstacksdk -> keystoneauth

keystoneauth only understand 'collect_timing' while the others only
conveys 'timing'. Therefore, we have to make the proper translation.

Change-Id: I6c1182bb1d8c04791a573fb556197440360a2bb9
Story: #2005315
Task: #30222
(cherry picked from commit 21bb881d03d431995c654313db7ba29035b3bcb1)

commit_message:
Enable fluentd monitoring in single and multinode jobs

This updates the scripts for deploying fluentd to include
overrides for enabling prometheus monitoring. Despite not
deploying prometheus in the osh-infra-logging job, we can still
leverage the post run job to gather metrics from the exporters
service. This gives us the means for verifying the functionality
of the exporter

Change-Id: Id98474de89d86419157635007e2f114f0947498e

commit_message:
Fix failing tips-py35 jobs

With Train, Python 3.5 is not a tested target anymore, switch to Python
3.6. This should fix all failing tips-py35 jobs.

Example failure:

commit_message:
Remove in-tree periodic job

The periodic job is defined in both openstack/project-config and here.
Remove it here and keep the version in project-config so that we can
update it easily for all projects for train.

Related changes:
* https://review.opendev.org/654571
* https://review.opendev.org/654574

Change-Id: I4408048391dc9a286d8d6ab8f8424a659b1b00ed
(cherry picked from commit 286e54d10a0bec1c01fe97cc1079e3dd1c1d9c22)

commit_message:
Fix pool protocol and algorithm validation

This patch fixes an issue where pool update would raise
UnsupportedOptionError for pool updates with protocol not altered.

It also adds validation for supported algorithms on pool create and
update.

Closes-Bug: #1822277

Change-Id: Ia957018dcb00486124db151ba30cf20505fb1656
(cherry picked from commit cf82db836a100093d1333bc86591abe880e2ae51)

commit_message:
Replace git.openstack.org with opendev.org

This patch replaces git.openstack.org with opendev.org as redirection
from old path was enabled.
Path do not fix path in run_tests.sh and scripts/scripts-library.sh as
I'm not really sure whether it's safe to change now.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/658295
Change-Id: I700fa432c88e77ca1b0e29667d04bfbb67829735
(cherry picked from commit ee8497176aed2cf849a00afbe5728bf909d4b1aa)

commit_message:
Modify udev rule for VF representor rename

It seems that if we have more than one NIC in SR_IOV switchdev mode,
the names of the represntors will overlap for those NICS,
like pf0vf0 for the first port of the first NIC and pf0vf0 for the
first port of the second NIC, so we need to rename the VF
representor as "<sriov_pf_name>_<vf_num>" "enp3s0f0_2" in order to
be unique and consistent

Change-Id: I25263926e736ed0e4fafaa9aa9891e5961226462
Closes-Bug: #1823526

messages: [{'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2019-05-11 18:52:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2019-05-11 20:52:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2019-05-12 01:34:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow+1\n\nI'm going to quick approve this as it's needed to unblock gates"}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-11 18:52:57.000000000', 'message': "Cap networkx, keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

NetworkX released 2.3, dropping support for Python 2.

https://github.com/networkx/networkx/blob/master/doc/news.rst

Includes squash of commit:
Change-Id: I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876
(cherry picked from commit d78bf07af26b6ff485722838b1c11e43796a115b)

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
(cherry picked from commit 00b2bcf7d664b1526b4eefe157c33113206d6251)
"}]
commit_message:
Cap networkx, keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

NetworkX released 2.3, dropping support for Python 2.

https://github.com/networkx/networkx/blob/master/doc/news.rst

Includes squash of commit:
Change-Id: I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876
(cherry picked from commit d78bf07af26b6ff485722838b1c11e43796a115b)

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
(cherry picked from commit 00b2bcf7d664b1526b4eefe157c33113206d6251)

commit_message:
Make utility install playbook idempotent

To ensure idempotence we do the following:

1. Ensure that the symlinks are only changed if
   they do not yet exist.
2. Switch the openstack client bash completion to
   be a handler which is executed whenever the
   venv changes or the symlinks change.

Change-Id: I6e3ae377c37fb8b72b5ff913154f7763d1691b25
(cherry picked from commit 2fe78ca4ea0b50a77f680b093f382bcb333ebdd7)

Change-Id: I1d95e4bbed051ea7e4bb77fb9e38d3006843f998
'}, {'created': '2019-05-06 23:09:47.000000000', 'message': 'Add Boto3 to global requirements.

Swift is moving to using Boto3, as opposed to the unmaintained Boto
library for its S3 tests.

* Is the library actively maintained?

Yes -- it is the recommended library by Amazon for AWS and S3
specifically. Last commit: 05/06/2019 (auto-commit). Maintainers respond
to bug reports.

* Is the library good code?

It's the evolution of the Boto library. The code is well documented,
with numerous examples of usage. A significant portion is
auto-generated, which makes working on the library a little more
difficult. The library supports extensions and modifications through its
event system, which allows its easier usage in the testing
infrastructure.

* Is the library python 3 compatible?

Yes -- up to python 3.7.

* Is  the library license compatible?

Boto3 is licensed under Apache 2.0.

* Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
latest / Fedora latest)?

Yes (Ubuntu 19.04: 1.9.86; Fedora 30: 1.9.101)

* Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries in
global-requirements.txt?

This would be a replacement for the existing Boto library. The older
Boto library could be removed if all users transition to Boto3.

* Is the library required for OpenStack project or related dev or
infrastructure setup? (Answer to this should be Yes, of course) Which?

Yes, it is to be used by Swift: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/657149/.
The Boto library has the following warning text:
"API updates and all new feature work will be focused on Boto3"
and:
"As more users make the switch to Boto3, we expect to reduce our
maintenance involvement over time".
Boto issues/pull requests are currently not addressed (for example,
https://github.com/Boto/Boto/pull/3471 and
https://github.com/Boto/Boto/pull/3513 -- pull requests from a Swift
committer have been open for 3 years with no feedback).

Boto and Boto3 can be used alongside each other to simplify the
transition.

* If the library release is managed by the Openstack release process
does it use the cycle-with-intermediary release type?

This is an external to OpenStack library.

Change-Id: I1d95e4bbed051ea7e4bb77fb9e38d3006843f998
'}]
commit_message:
Add Boto3 to global requirements.

Swift is moving to using Boto3, as opposed to the unmaintained Boto
library for its S3 tests.

* Is the library actively maintained?

Yes -- it is the recommended library by Amazon for AWS and S3
specifically. Last commit: 05/06/2019 (auto-commit). Maintainers respond
to bug reports.

* Is the library good code?

It's the evolution of the Boto library. The code is well documented,
with numerous examples of usage. A significant portion is
auto-generated, which makes working on the library a little more
difficult. The library supports extensions and modifications through its
event system, which allows its easier usage in the testing
infrastructure.

* Is the library python 3 compatible?

Yes -- up to python 3.7.

* Is  the library license compatible?

Boto3 is licensed under Apache 2.0.

* Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
latest / Fedora latest)?

Yes (Ubuntu 19.04: 1.9.86; Fedora 30: 1.9.101)

* Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries in
global-requirements.txt?

This would be a replacement for the existing Boto library. The older
Boto library could be removed if all users transition to Boto3.

* Is the library required for OpenStack project or related dev or
infrastructure setup? (Answer to this should be Yes, of course) Which?

Yes, it is to be used by Swift: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/657149/.
The Boto library has the following warning text:
"API updates and all new feature work will be focused on Boto3"
and:
"As more users make the switch to Boto3, we expect to reduce our
maintenance involvement over time".
Boto issues/pull requests are currently not addressed (for example,
https://github.com/Boto/Boto/pull/3471 and
https://github.com/Boto/Boto/pull/3513 -- pull requests from a Swift
committer have been open for 3 years with no feedback).

Boto and Boto3 can be used alongside each other to simplify the
transition.

* If the library release is managed by the Openstack release process
does it use the cycle-with-intermediary release type?

This is an external to OpenStack library.

Change-Id: I1d95e4bbed051ea7e4bb77fb9e38d3006843f998

commit_message:
Fix the stable/stein branch gate

This patch contains two fixes to unblock the stable/stein gate:

1. Change networking-ovn tripleo job to run against fs10

Right now, scenario03 (fs18) is broken in TripleO. This patch
is changing the job definition in our gate to use fs10 instead.
We should revert this once TripleO fixes sc03 to have a more
complete testing (pacemaker, mistral, ...).

2. Blacklist bandit 1.6.0 due to directory exclusion bug

Bandit 1.6.0 introduces a regression with the -x option.

Change-Id: I429be059743ce6ae79a0b68ed1fac6b307e5e4b1
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez Sanchez <dalvarez@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 400de6eb5eaa56ceab90d535a458bb90ab6673d3)

commit_message:
Ensure that pip/setuptools/wheel python wheels are built

All virtualenvs make use of pip/setuptools/wheel, but none of
them specify that these wheels need to be built and therefore
every venv build process reaches out to pypi to fetch them.

To ensure that the repo container has these built as wheels,
we set the utility container to build them so that these
packages will be available for other venvs to use.

Change-Id: I60f851e1ffa401c92221de14651502306e9b0581
(cherry picked from commit bd69ca0b8a197c3986e1fdcfcc12f6e552ad66d2)

commit_message:
DNM: two dumb downstream things to fix, IGNORE ME

Neither of these needs to be like this. Internal cruft.
The netmask change just needs to be a custom template and the config
should be changed to read it.
The requirements thing should go away if i just switch to gunicorn as a
runner, or add uwsgi to the custom kolla stuff for octavia builds.

Just added a third, which is a temp fix to allow failing over old amps.

Change-Id: Ibd5a838445df1a2b7d8672ded0748f7dc9ba9eb9

commit_message:
[OpenStackAnsible] create pike-em tag against final releases

This is a procedural review to transition pike into extended
maintenance by creating the pike-em tag.

It's possible that the release isn't needed (for example if
there are no code changes sine the previous release, sadly
that's non-trivial to detect en masse).

If you are the PTL or release liaison for this team please +1
this review if it is ready or -1 and take over the review to
correct mistakes.

Change-Id: I727699d870c2c6544ebe9f463da8753eb39f46f1

commit_message:
Increase coverage of leap 15 jobs

I added an experimental test, to have metal + packages. It should
also be stable, and show if packaging is failing. That testing
could be used by SUSE to gate the packaging.

Change-Id: I99312ed8b1d222e977e71e9e825d52ecfc9b48ae

In https://review.opendev.org/648556 we release noted the removal of
the pypiserver service, but nothing has actually removed it during
the upgrade process.

This patch implements the removal. This is implemented as a handler

Change-Id: I06367f3448a4d2bd932d868cd7ea825287b84fbc
'}]
commit_message:
Major Upgrade: Remove pypiserver from repo server

In https://review.opendev.org/648556 we release noted the removal of
the pypiserver service, but nothing has actually removed it during
the upgrade process.

This patch implements the removal. This is implemented as a handler
to ensure that the service and nginx config are removed only when
the changes are made to the service restarts.

Change-Id: I06367f3448a4d2bd932d868cd7ea825287b84fbc

commit_message:
Cap keyring, scikit-learn, and sphinx on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

Similarly sphinx 2.0.0 drop py27 support do express that in
global-requirements.

There isn't a need to update u-c as they're already correct:
  $ grep -E '^(Sphinx|keyring)' upper-constraints.txt
  keyring===18.0.1;python_version=='2.7'
  keyring===19.0.1;python_version=='3.4'
  keyring===19.0.1;python_version=='3.5'
  keyring===19.0.1;python_version=='3.6'
  Sphinx===1.8.5;python_version=='2.7'
  Sphinx===2.0.1;python_version=='3.4'
  Sphinx===2.0.1;python_version=='3.5'
  Sphinx===2.0.1;python_version=='3.6'

This may cause knock-on effects for projects using either of these in
lower-constraints, but that's less impactful than all the 'red' in the
gate right now

Also 'correct' the Sphinx requirement in test-requirements so we get the
correct version when running under python2.  We need to do this anyway as
docs jobs typically run unconstrained

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c

commit_message:
Add storing introspection data in database option

Ironic-inspector database is a default config for
our devstack deploy. Sometimes we won't to use Swift,
and directly use database for store data.

This patch adds a variable for introspection
store_data.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/658238/
Change-Id: I6a8888b778f517bee49705ee74463ae39b2b9163

commit_message:
Use doc/requirements to fix python-jobs

Sphinx 2.0.1 needs python3 - so, move it out of test-requirements.txt to
unblock python jobs.

Also, update doc building to use current commands following PTI.

Note that we use python3 for building of docs, so no need to have cap
Sphinx for python2 anymore.

Change-Id: Iee97d8546ec50c75677ed82454e9e248fba0db2f

commit_message:
Fixup README

To be able to make a release README.rst should follow some
convention.

This change fixes that.

NOTE(tonyb): This pike backport adds a cap on sphinx to <2.0.0.  This is
needed because the Telemetry team prefer the NOT us constraints and
2.0.0 is available and removed the ability to use the Sphinx object for
logging.
NOTE(tonyb): This chnage also switches to the 'PTI' version of the docs
templates to ensure that all the required packages are installed

Change-Id: Ib4d1fd628bb0374586146b11dfafa0b243b3f084
(cherry picked from commit 6d1ad0fba7fe4790a19eefc6b8f9d506674720ae)
(cherry picked from commit 391c97c37043f940619b29b7a66b1ccbb3486bbb)

commit_message:
Skip image validation if failed

This allows image validation to fail and continue lauching the
container. This is because image validation might depend on
external image registry (i.e. DockerHub) which is not always stable.

Change-Id: I3c65cdef17d8279233bfbb74a38c9db79b01a2de
Closes-Bug: #1827968

commit_message:
Use hashes for the upgrade playbook markers

The run-upgrades script only checked and used the base filename of
a playbook when creating markers for each completed playbook.
This prevented the same playbook from being run multiple times with
different provided extra variables, each subsequent run of the same
playbook would be skipped.

Instead use hashed values of each entire playbook run item string as the
markers of completed upgrade playbooks.

Change-Id: If2733f12d45c1a0e0d7fb799e2520e0696a453f7
Co-Authored-By: Jesse Pretorius <jesse@odyssey4.me>
(cherry picked from commit e5ba603880d2465ce903dcff2bc2e95d9f896c8a)

offending rules so we can do the final release.

204 Lines should be no longer than 160 chars

'}]
commit_message:
Ignore ansible-lint issues

We're working on doing a final release of tripleo-validations and the
ansible-lint rules have changed since we last did anything on this
branch. Rather than fixing all the files, let's just ignore the biggest
offending rules so we can do the final release.

204 Lines should be no longer than 160 chars
306 Shells that use pipes should set the pipefail option
602 Don't compare to empty string

I addressed the "206 Variables should have spaces before and after: {{
var_name }}" issue in haproxy.yaml since it was only a single instance.

Change-Id: I96630f3e29f9143fc8dcbbc6aeb8262187023417

commit_message:
Correct error messages on update network form

The name is not required, so data["name"] may be empty.
When data["name"] is empty, get the id value.
This patch correct error messages on update network form

commit_message:
Set CentOS 7 distro job to non-voting

We need to merge https://review.opendev.org/#/c/656891/ to unblock
the gate, but RDO packging for nova is broken[1] and is preventing
us from merging anything currently. We should make it non-voting to
get the gates working again, work on removing the nova-placement-api
package from the nova role, and then re-enable voting.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/657398/

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/658286
Change-Id: Id9bd94923e05b3911a9dfd4e10c43f4c0ab81b9b
(cherry picked from commit 9b1228e658945c3b6b173a5f94ad2e9052739ae2)

This goal is to implement the process set out in the 2018-10-24 Python
Update Process TC resolution[1], for the Train cycle to ensure unit
testing is in place for all of the Tested Runtimes for Train[2].
Using the Zuul template for Train will ensure that all projects that
support Python3 will be tested against the agreed runtime versions,
and make it easier to update them in future.

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20181024-python-update-process.html

commit_message:
Use zuul template for python3 test runtime

This goal is to implement the process set out in the 2018-10-24 Python
Update Process TC resolution[1], for the Train cycle to ensure unit
testing is in place for all of the Tested Runtimes for Train[2].
Using the Zuul template for Train will ensure that all projects that
support Python3 will be tested against the agreed runtime versions,
and make it easier to update them in future.

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20181024-python-update-process.html
[2]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/train.html

Change-Id: I406a4f1ecbff5b6c8e18ff1b93a3b2ceef49343a

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-10 04:18:17.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Pep8 bandit error

Make bandit runs with 1.6.0

bandit 1.6.0 was released today:
https://pypi.org/project/bandit/1.6.0/

And is uncapped in test-requirements:
https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/test-requirements.txt#L18

And not in upper-constraints:
https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/upper-constraints.txt

The -x option for bandit changed in 1.6.0 and now
supports glob patterns so use that to correctly
exclude test code from bandit scans.

Seems we should exclude test code from bandit scans.

Change-Id: If93ba1ae6374f10d8713a3e7cb17639314729c4a
'}, {'created': '2019-05-10 06:07:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Pep8 bandit error and Uncap jsonschema

Make bandit runs with 1.6.0

bandit 1.6.0 was released today:
https://pypi.org/project/bandit/1.6.0/

And is uncapped in test-requirements:
https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/test-requirements.txt#L18

And not in upper-constraints:
https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/upper-constraints.txt

The -x option for bandit changed in 1.6.0 and now
supports glob patterns so use that to correctly
exclude test code from bandit scans.

commit_message:
Fix Pep8 bandit error and Uncap jsonschema

Make bandit runs with 1.6.0

bandit 1.6.0 was released today:
https://pypi.org/project/bandit/1.6.0/

And is uncapped in test-requirements:
https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/test-requirements.txt#L18

And not in upper-constraints:
https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/upper-constraints.txt

The -x option for bandit changed in 1.6.0 and now
supports glob patterns so use that to correctly
exclude test code from bandit scans.

Seems we should exclude test code from bandit scans.

About Uncap jsonschema please see:
Reference commit:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/649799/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/649669/2/global-requirements.txt

Change-Id: If93ba1ae6374f10d8713a3e7cb17639314729c4a

commit_message:
Remove OVNTunnelEncapType

The only OVN Tunnel Encap Type that we are supporting in OVN is Geneve
and this is set by default in ovn puppet. So there are no need to set
it in TripleO

Change-Id: Ide08d028d3311dfd08ee3872b32ebd1e1a36e17b
Closes-Bug: 1828186

commit_message:
Blacklist bandit 1.6.0

There's a regression[0] in bandit 1.6.0 which causes bandit to stop
respecting excluded directories, and our tests throw a bunch of
violations. Blacklist this version, but allow newer versions as there is
already a pull request[1] to fix it, and I expect it will be included in
the next release.

[0] https://github.com/PyCQA/bandit/issues/488
[1] https://github.com/PyCQA/bandit/pull/489

Change-Id: Ie4dbfb3f54e4aac00e0537d5760b7a8fc81b35a2

commit_message:
Async notify neutron-server for HA states

RPC notifier method can sometimes be time-consuming,
this will cause other parallel processing resources
fail to send notifications in time. This patch changes
the notify to asynchronous.

Closes-Bug: #1824911
Change-Id: I3f555a0c78fbc02d8214f12b62c37d140bc71da1

commit_message:
workbooks/deployment: add support to filter nodes when running Ansible

In run_ansible task, adding support to filter nodes with limit_hosts
(--limit option in Ansible), so we can call the workbook with the desire
to run Ansible only on certain hosts (e.g. scale down).

Change-Id: I1aa086cc706110905b7a45a765d67d01ee90434e

subject: Use RpcPort for container healthchecks
revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-10 13:26:39.000000000', 'message': "Use RpcPort for container healthchecks

Update healthcheck commands that probe oslo's messaging port to use the
RpcPort parameter. Previously, some templates referenced the service's
own 'rabbit_port' config setting, which led to malformed healthcheck
commands when the 'rabbit_port' settings were deprecated.

Update the templates that looked up the port in the RabbitMQService's
global_config_settings. Not only did this break the oslo abstraction
by referring to a specific messaging backend (rabbit), it broke
split-stack deployments in which the RabbitMQService is not actually
deployed on the secondary stack's nodes.

This patch creates a common healthcheck command using the RpcPort
parameter in containers-common.yaml. This allows other templates to
reference a common healthcheck command. Other templates that should
also use this can be cleaned up in a separate patch.

Closes-Bug: #1825342
Change-Id: I0d3974089ae6e6879adab4852715c7a1c1188f7c
(cherry picked from commit c5fe51147b53e032d2e87cf7c792d8459098b42e)
Conflicts:
	deployment/heat/heat-engine-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-compute-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-ironic-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-scheduler-container-puppet.yaml
"}]
commit_message:
Use RpcPort for container healthchecks

Update healthcheck commands that probe oslo's messaging port to use the
RpcPort parameter. Previously, some templates referenced the service's
own 'rabbit_port' config setting, which led to malformed healthcheck
commands when the 'rabbit_port' settings were deprecated.

Update the templates that looked up the port in the RabbitMQService's
global_config_settings. Not only did this break the oslo abstraction
by referring to a specific messaging backend (rabbit), it broke
split-stack deployments in which the RabbitMQService is not actually
deployed on the secondary stack's nodes.

This patch creates a common healthcheck command using the RpcPort
parameter in containers-common.yaml. This allows other templates to
reference a common healthcheck command. Other templates that should
also use this can be cleaned up in a separate patch.

Closes-Bug: #1825342
Change-Id: I0d3974089ae6e6879adab4852715c7a1c1188f7c
(cherry picked from commit c5fe51147b53e032d2e87cf7c792d8459098b42e)
Conflicts:
	deployment/heat/heat-engine-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-compute-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-ironic-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/nova/nova-scheduler-container-puppet.yaml

commit_message:
[neutron] create pike-em tag against final releases

This is a procedural review to transition pike into extended
maintenance by creating the pike-em tag.

It's possible that the release isn't needed (for example if
there are no code changes sine the previous release, sadly
that's non-trivial to detect en masse).

If you are the PTL or release liaison for this team please +1
this review if it is ready or -1 and take over the review to
correct mistakes.

Change-Id: I1b88befeafc0a954fb99add3a6fbf404916ecfdb

commit_message:
Adapt plugin to new q- n- syntax

Currently, the neutron-lbaas plugin has issues as it's not setting nor
storing the proper value for Q_PLUGIN_FILE so the lbaasv2 plugin fails
to install completely while trying to do a neutron-manage db-update.

Change-Id: I1ed6eba65cbc492f1eca63a1264e626cfe1aa779

commit_message:
Create new network resources during tempest scenario test

The existing loadbalancer scneario test will use the first tenant network in
user project or the configured fixed_network_name in tempest.conf, which
is not flexiable since in production the resources of tempest test are
better to be purged periodically for resource cleanup.

Like the neutron tempest network scneario test, change to create new
smoke network/subnet/router during the test instead.

Change-Id: I61ddb482f46ae51aeed366c3603fc1c2e838a4d5

commit_message:
Driver easy duplication support

Driver configuration section name is dynamic now.
New driver class in a separate module may be easilly created.
The inheritting class just need to pass its __name__ to the base
RadwareLBaaSV2Driver class __init__ function.
Unit tests updated.

Closes-Bug: 1728358

Change-Id: Ic2763c9101954d33913f5133ab784def295b9590

commit_message:
Modify the way controls certificates show or hide

In create load balancer form, when protocol selects TERMINATED_HTTPS,
the certificates should be displayed in navigation bar, otherwise,
it should be hide.

Change-Id: Ic0aab9c6771c68b6631c2dc9ae51481cd31f0376
Closes-bug: #1797351

neutron-lbaas has been deprecated since the Queens release of OpenStack. No new feature enhancements are allowed.
If you feel this is an existing bug, please open a storyboard story for the issue and associate the story and task with the patch.
At first read, this appears to be a feature enhancement to support NDBCluster in MySQL and would not be approved for merge.
Octavia is replacing neutron-lbaas, you are welcome to propose a similar change for Octavia as the go forward project.
I will also note, we cannot change existing migration scripts. Anyone upgrading an existing neutron-lbaas environment would not get this change. All schema changes must be their own migration.

commit_message:
Hardcode foreignkey constraint name for lbaas_listeners

Few database engines like MySQL NDBCluster generates random names for
foreign key constraints. So, to make it easy while droping these
constraints (for example, 6aee0434f911_independent_pools.py), hardcode
the constraint name.

Change-Id: I20e7e8bc5cee5945cfa1ab1050792a262c3a9bc1

commit_message:
Make subnet_id an optional parameter for pool members

While it may be required for some underlying SDN implementations,
some others may not be interested in subnet_id.

Change-Id: I4e3c692034b62f2742efa9513b335129bc576d08

commit_message:
Cannot delete a pool if a healthmonitor attached

If we deleted a pool which a healthmonitor attached, when we
update/delete this healthmonitor, it will raise exception for
its root_loadbalancer(self.pool.listener.loadbalancer) doesn't
contain any pool.

Change-Id: I02532cb66337c7d225f221f30483ccfe98c7f685

commit_message:
tempest: healthmonitor is deleted via resource_cleanup

No need for an explicit cleanup. Explicit cleanup of monitors deleted by
resource_cleanup causes tempest tests to fail

Change-Id: I3f6c53bb23bc4fd84581b18ec847d52ade3d1ac6
Closes-bug: 1709602

'}, {'created': '2017-06-29 05:18:34.000000000', 'message': "Update members data based on haproxy stats data.

Related-Bug: #1699945

Users in the process of using LBAAS service, not only
need to check LBAAS own monitoring data, but also need
to check the real servers (members) status and monitoring
data, Because it can be check real servers specific real-time
processing capabilities, and convenient for real server
resource adjustment. Most importantly, the status and data
of the real server in the background can provide data support
for intelligent operations in the future.

In addition, users can extend the required statistics items

commit_message:
Update members data based on haproxy stats data.

Users in the process of using lbaas service, not only need
to check lbaas own monitoring data, but also need to check
the real servers (members) status and monitoring data,Because
it could be check real servers real-time processing capabilities,
and convenient for real server resource adjustment.Most importantly,
the status and data of the real server in the background could be
provide data support for intelligent operations in the future.

In addition, users can extend the required statistics items
of members as long as haproxy support.

1.Adds the new file for creating new migration to add new column.
2.Collect the members stats data and write these data to database.(table_name:lbaas_loadbalancer_statistics)
3.Using the neutron lbaas-loadbalancer-stats [lb_id], Users can check
  the corresponding loadblancer statistics data,Including members'
  statistics of the loadblancer.

Related-Bug: #1699945
Change-Id: I77be7edfc1a662c7962bdd9af2f6457ff2c2cb25

commit_message:
Modify the ip of member in tests

According to bug 1585890, the address of member should be in the
cidr of its subnets.
The address of member in testcase is usually 127.0.0.1,but the
cidr of its subnets is 10.0.0.0/24.
Modify the ip of member to fix the cidr:10.0.0.0/24

Change-Id: Iee829eeff0040d7fdbfc713d392ed65b4ef222dd

So, my question was really "are you sure this is right?" because I actually am not sure -- I ASSUMED it would work the same as Python range() because otherwise that would be horribly inconsistent, but maybe you are correct and it does not? I need to dig into the code a little to find out, I was just hoping you could provide proof in some way to save me some time. :P'}, {'account_id': 21614, 'date': '2016-07-26 02:04:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

To Adam Harwell:
 'validate': {'type:range': [0, 256]}。
It is not the same as python range(0,256).
The check is in func _validate_range(neutron/api/v2/attributes.py)
min_value = valid_values[0]
max_value = valid_values[1]
if max_value is not UNLIMITED and data > max_value:
        msg = _("'%(data)s' is too large - must be no larger than "
                "'%(limit)d'") % {'data': data, 'limit': max_value}
        LOG.debug(msg)
        return msg
So if data is 256,it does not larger than 256,and we can create member
with weight 256.'}, {'account_id': 7293, 'date': '2016-08-04 10:51:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Modify the range of weight in member

Weight in member is created with the range [0,256],
and usually it is [0,255]
'weight': {'allow_post': True, 'allow_put': True,
                       'default': 1,
                       'validate': {'type:range': [0, 256],
                                    'type:integer': None},
                       'is_visible': True},

Change-Id: I172a87e58ee0e30b5f1c7a769505ac2da9d69933

commit_message:
Neutron-LBaaS v2: Barbican TLS Scenario Test

* scenario test that does the following:
 1.  Create 1 compute server and run 2 web server on it
 2.  Create SSL Cert, Private Key with intermediates
 3.  Upload SSL Cert and Private Key to Barbican secrets and get their reference
 4.  Create Barbican TLS container with secrets reference
 4.  Create Load Balancer and pass in Barbican TLS container reference
 5.  Pass SSL traffic to load balancer
 6.  Verify SSL traffic to node

Clean-up is required for all the scenario tests which will be
pushed in separate commit

Co-Authored-By: Phillip Toohill <phillip.toohill@rackspace.com>
Co-Authored-By: Madhusudhan Kandadai <madhusudhan.openstack@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I748d6b23ba64e4016b3dc5997fedd517eab0df35
Closes-Bug: #1577543

commit_message:
Enable MySQL Cluster Support for neutron-lbaas

This enables the usage of the mysql_enable_ndb setting from oslo.db
from bug 1564110.This allows operators to select from MySQL (InnoDB)
or MySQL Cluster (NDB) as the storage engine backend.

Depends-On: I597d6ab50fe117e725f1d8de9b359ac9fbb79eb3
Depends-On: I9f1fd2a87fdf75332de2339d3ff4f08ce9220dcf
Change-Id: I1ac4724f5d461368e9db720190c0fe728739f3f1
Implements: blueprint mysql-cluster-support

commit_message:
Expose provisioning_status and operating_status for all top level objects

Expose provisioning_status and operating_status for listener, pool, member
and healthmonitor. We can fetch the provisioning_status of these objects
with this patch.

Related-Bug: #1632054
Change-Id: I7622e353846134795f28ffb03ddb2f976008779e

commit_message:
py3: deal with more subordinate dependencies

Ensure subordinate py3 packages are installed if their py2
counter-parts are currently installed for neutron-openvswitch.
In this case we had missed python(3)-neutron-fwaas.

Change-Id: I9d5e7c2ad034cd7bdf9cbf292b9107577860dac1
Closes-Bug: #1828259
(cherry picked from commit 96b5e8a2493305ec7667c153d070dffda1bf547b)

commit_message:
Continue refactoring of the image

Next refactoring monster with:
- switch bunch of cloud._image methods to using image.proxy methods
- Add new image.Image attribute
- Fix image properties by adding global support for keeping "unknown"
attributes under properties attr
- turn back function lost in openstackcloud split (sadly not found by
unittests)
- add ability to create image without data required by OSC to switch to
SDK
- use the proxy logger

Change-Id: I9d36d3a52370d6a1040362e1d6e762146df86258

commit_message:
[redhat] Install rsync-daemon for newer releases

The newer packages havee moved rsyncd into its own package called
rsync-daemon so we'll install that for anything newer than EL7.

Change-Id: Id1e8cc503d71cf6e7d0d84b5a74f6c3d7bce9393

commit_message:
DNM: use SqlFixture from neutron-lib

DO NOT MERGE: STILL IN TEST PHASE

A SqlFixture already lives in neutron-lib and can be used in place of
neutron's SqlFixture, StaticSqlFixture and StaticSqlFixtureNoSchema.
This patch removes those from neutron and switches over to use
neutron-lib's SqlFixture instead.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/651629/

commit_message:
[ipaclient] Fix type of MakeHomeDir heat param

https://review.opendev.org/#/c/650899 added this new
Heat Parameter but set type to 'bool', the correct type
is 'boolean', this patch fixes it.

Also change the comparison in shell script to handle
both True/true by converting the variable to lower case.

Related-Bug: #1823727
Change-Id: I52ba523ecbfd8282858e3102b29189d8ce287a26

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-04-25 11:12:37.000000000', 'message': 'Update SEV trait docs to avoid misleading people

Since the AMD SEV spec was approved for Stein, it was subsequently
realised that a trait would not be sufficient for tracking SEV-capable
compute hosts.  A resource class is also needed to track the inventory
of "slots" available on these hosts, since the number of slots limits
how many guests with encrypted memory can run concurrently.

Therefore the design pivoted somewhat, and now
trait:HW_CPU_AMD_SEV=required will not be the correct way to request
SEV functionality:

  https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/train/approved/amd-sev-libvirt-support.html

For reference, the previous spec is here:

  https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/stein/approved/amd-sev-libvirt-support.html

Another lesson learnt from the Stein cycle was that it is not safe to
assume that the work targeted for one cycle will actually land in that
cycle, therefore it's safer for documentation of an in-progress
feature to be transparent that it's in progress and not yet usable.

Change-Id: I6b652c20ba4f5ec775829a45939d708066dc3011
blueprint: amd-sev-libvirt-support

blueprint: amd-sev-libvirt-support
